Analysis 1: Analyze the price trends of train tickets on the different routes and study how the prices vary with the number of days before departure.

all_data <- read.csv(here("Scrapped data", "all_data.csv"))

#Calculate the number of days to purchase tickets in advance
all_data$days_to_departure <- as.integer(round(difftime(all_data$departure_date, all_data$scrapping_date, units = "days")))

#Select routes:Madrid â Barcelona, Madrid â Alicante, and Madrid â Zaragoza
all_data$route <- paste(all_data$departure_station, all_data$arrival_station, sep = " â ")

# Manually create isometric mappings
day_mapping <- data.frame(
  original = c(1, 7, 14, 30),
  mapped = c(0, 1, 2, 3) 
)

 # Mapping by join
  all_data <- all_data %>%
  left_join(day_mapping, by = c("days_to_departure" = "original")) %>%
  mutate(mapped_days = ifelse(is.na(mapped), NA, mapped)) 
  
 # Data visualization
  ggplot(all_data, aes(x = mapped_days, y = price, color = scrapping_web)) +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE, size = 1.2, span = 0.6) +  
    facet_wrap(~route, scales = "free_y") + 
    
    scale_color_manual(name = "Operator",
                       values = c("Trainline" = "#539980",  
                                  "Ouigo" = "#dc0067", 
                                  "Renfe" = "#820064")) +  
    
    # Make X-axis 1, 7, 14, 30 equidistant
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0, 1, 2, 3), labels = c("1", "7", "14", "30")) +  
    
    # Y-axis scale refinement
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(all_data$price, na.rm = TRUE), by = 3)) +  
    
    # Title & Theme Optimization
    labs(title = "Train Ticket Price Trends by Route",
         subtitle = "How ticket prices vary with days before departure",
         x = "Days Before Departure",
         y = "Average Ticket Price (â¬)",
         color = "Operator") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"),
          plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12),
          legend.position = "bottom")

This visualization illustrates the price trends of three major train routes in Spain (Madrid â Alicante, Madrid â Barcelona, and Madrid â Zaragoza). The horizontal axis represents the number of days in advance the ticket is purchased (1, 7, 14, 30 days), while the vertical axis shows the average ticket price (â¬). Different colors indicate different train operators or ticketing platforms (Trainline, Ouigo, Renfe).

Renfe: Typically has the highest prices, especially on the Madrid â Barcelona and Madrid â Zaragoza routes, indicating its pricing strategy as a traditional railway operator.

Ouigo: Consistently offers the lowest fares, particularly on the Madrid â Alicante route, where prices remain stable at around â¬30, reflecting its low-cost operating strategy.

Trainline: As a ticketing platform aggregating multiple railway operators, its prices represent the average fare levels on each route. Its price trends generally fall between Renfe and Ouigo, reflecting the overall pricing strategies of different ticket providers on the same routes.

Booking in advance generally results in lower prices on the Madrid â Alicante route, with all operators showing a downward price trend, especially Renfe and Trainline. However, on the Madrid â Barcelona and Madrid â Zaragoza routes, prices tend to rise around 7 to 14 days before departure, likely due to higher short-term demand.

For the best fares:

Madrid â Alicante: The lowest prices are found when booking 7â14 days in advance, after which prices stabilize.

Madrid â Barcelona & Madrid â Zaragoza: Booking 30 days in advance often offers better deals, as prices tend to peak around 7â14 days before departure. ## Analysis 2:Train Ticket Pricing, Travel Duration, and Cost-Effectiveness Analysis by Time Period & Booking Website

color_mapping <- c("Trainline" = "#539980", "Ouigo" = "#dc0067", "Renfe" = "#820064")

# 2. define the time period
all_data2$time_period <- case_when(
  all_data2$departure_hour >= 6 & all_data2$departure_hour < 12 ~ "Morning",
  all_data2$departure_hour >= 12 & all_data2$departure_hour < 18 ~ "Afternoon",
  all_data2$departure_hour >= 18 & all_data2$departure_hour < 24 ~ "Evening",
  TRUE ~ "Night"
)
# 3. Calculate the average ticket price, travel duration, and price per minute for different websites across different time periods.
website_analysis <- all_data2 |> 
  filter(!is.na(price)) |>  
  group_by(scrapping_web, time_period) |>

    avg_price = mean(price, na.rm = TRUE),

The results of the analysis show that there are significant differences in fares, travel time and value for money between the different ticketing websites at different times of the day.

  1. Price trends: Ouigo lowest, Renfe highest In terms of price trends, Ouigoâs fares are significantly lower than the other sites at all times of day, especially in the morning (Morning) when fares are the lowest at around â¬37.1, making it the best value for money option. In contrast, Renfe has the highest fares in the afternoon and evening hours, especially in the afternoon, where the average fare is â¬60.7, significantly higher than on the other sites.

  2. Duration trends: Renfe has the longest travel times in the morning hours In terms of travel time, Renfe has the longest average travel time in the morning (152.5 minutes), which is significantly longer than Ouigo and Trainline. This may be due to the fact that there are fewer trains in the morning, or that some of the trains run slower.

  3. Value for money analysis: Ouigo offers the best value for money in all time slots In terms of value for money (price/minute), Ouigo offers better value for money than the other websites at all times of the day, especially in the morning, when fares are the lowest and travel times are moderate, making it the most economical choice. trainlineâs fares are slightly higher than Ouigoâs, but the travel times are shorter, making it still the better choice in some cases. renfe offers the lowest value for money, especially in the morning, due to the lower frequency or longer travel times. Renfe is the least cost-effective, especially in the morning hours, due to the longer travel time, resulting in higher overall fares and higher cost per minute.

  4. fares vs.Â travel time: longer doesnât mean cheaper Looking at the bubble chart, there is no clear negative correlation between fares and travel time. Normally, we would think that the longer the travel time, the cheaper the fare might be, but this is not the case in this analysis. For example, some Renfe trains have higher fares but also longer travel times, resulting in poor overall value for money. Ouigo and Trainline, on the other hand, are able to offer lower fares while maintaining shorter travel times, giving them an advantage in terms of value for money.

Analysis 3: Analyze the price difference between prices on Trainline and prices on official websites (Renfe/Ouigo)

renfe_ouigo <- bind_rows(renfe, ouigo)

trainline_price<- trainline |> 
  dplyr::select(c("departure_time","departure_station","arrival_station","price","train_company",
                  "departure_date","scrapping_date")) |> 
  mutate(key=paste0(departure_time,departure_station,arrival_station,train_company,departure_date,scrapping_date)) |> 
  dplyr::select(key, price) |> 
  rename(trainline_price=price)

price_difference <- renfe_ouigo |> 
  dplyr::select(c("departure_time","departure_station","arrival_station","price","train_company",
                  "departure_date","scrapping_date")) |> 
  mutate(key=paste0(departure_time,departure_station,arrival_station,train_company,departure_date,scrapping_date)) |> 
  inner_join(trainline_price, by="key") |> 
  dplyr::select(-key) |> 
  drop_na() |> 
  mutate(difference=trainline_price-price) |> 
  mutate(days_in_advance=departure_date-scrapping_date) |> 
  mutate(days_in_advance=as.factor(days_in_advance))

summary<- price_difference |> 
  summarise(average_price_difference=mean(difference),
            .by=c(arrival_station,days_in_advance,train_company))



ggplot(summary, aes(x = days_in_advance, y = arrival_station, fill = average_price_difference)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "green", mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 0) +
  labs(
    title = "Price difference between buying in Trainline\nand in original website (Renfe/Ouigo)",      
    subtitle = "Price difference = trainline price - price on Renfe/Ouigo official website\nDeparture city: Madrid",  
    x = "Number of days in advance to purchase tickets",           
    y = "Arrival city",            
    fill = "Average price\ndifference (â¬)"           
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ train_company) +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"),  
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10, color = "gray40"),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),  
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),  
    panel.background = element_blank()   
  )

Prices on Trainline website are cheaper in the green blocks within this plot, where we can discover several insights:

  1. There is no price advantage on Trainline website if the destination is Alicante.
  2. If the destination is Zaragoza, prices of Ouigo trains are cheaper on Trainline in general, but prices of Renfe trains are only cheaper for more than 14 days in advance to purchase tickets.
  3. If the destination is Barcelona, prices of Ouigo trains are cheaper on Trainline if we purchase for the next day or 30 days in advance; while for Renfe AVE trains, the prices of the next day will increase significantly on Trainline, but will be cheaper if we purchase for 14 days in advance.
  4. For Renfe AVLO trains, itâs only cheaper on Trainline if the destination is Zaragoza and we are purchasing for the next day.
  5. Finally, the range of average price differences (-2.5, 5.21) is pretty narrow, which means that most of the trains remain the same or similar prices on Trainline, only a few exceptions are cheaper or more expensive.
